## Best Practices for Accessibility Testing

1. **Test with actual assistive technologies**: Accerciser shows the data, but Orca shows the user experience
2. **Verify the entire interaction flow**: Don't just check static properties—test navigation, input, and state changes
3. **Test with keyboard only**: Disconnect your mouse and navigate your entire application
4. **Check color contrast**: Use tools like Contrast Checker alongside Accerciser
5. **Test across desktop environments**: GNOME, KDE, and XFCE may expose different theme information
6. **Validate dynamic content**: Ensure live regions announce updates appropriately
7. **Test error states**: Verify that validation errors are exposed to screen readers

Accerciser is your window into how assistive technologies perceive your application. Regular testing ensures OpenMaui applications remain accessible to all users.

## Accessibility Best Practices

Building accessible applications requires more than just implementing AT-SPI2 interfaces—it demands thoughtful design decisions throughout your development process. These best practices ensure your OpenMaui applications serve all users effectively.

## 1. Design for Keyboard-First Interaction

Every feature accessible with a mouse must be equally accessible via keyboard:

```csharp
// ❌ Bad: Mouse-only interaction
new SkiaImage
{
    Source = "close.svg",
    GestureRecognizers =
    {
        new TapGestureRecognizer 
        { 
            Command = CloseCommand 
        }
    }
};

// ✅ Good: Keyboard and mouse accessible
new SkiaImageButton
{
    Source = "close.svg",
    Command = CloseCommand,
    AccessibleName = "Close window",
    Focusable = true,
    // Responds to Enter, Space, and click
};
```

## 2. Provide Meaningful Text Alternatives

Every non-text element must have a text equivalent:

```csharp
// Images
new SkiaImage
{
    Source = "chart.svg",
    AccessibleName = "Sales trend chart showing 23% growth in Q4",
    AccessibleDescription = "Line graph with monthly sales data from January to December"
};

// Icon buttons
new SkiaImageButton
{
    Source = "edit.svg",
    AccessibleName = "Edit contact",
    Command = EditCommand
};

// Decorative images (no semantic meaning)
new SkiaImage
{
    Source = "decorative-pattern.svg",
    AccessibleRole = AccessibleRole.Unknown,
    // Screen readers will skip this
};
```

## 3. Use Semantic Structure

Organize content with proper headings and landmarks:

```csharp
public class ArticlePage : SkiaContentPage
{
    public ArticlePage()
    {
        Content = new SkiaStackLayout
        {
            Children =
            {
                // Main heading
                new SkiaLabel
