AT-SPI2 uses a hierarchical model where each UI element is represented as an **accessible object** with a specific role, state, and set of properties. OpenMaui implements comprehensive role mapping for all 35+ controls, ensuring screen readers can accurately describe your application's interface.

## Accessible Roles in OpenMaui

The platform supports over 40 accessible roles from the AT-SPI2 specification:

```csharp
public enum AccessibleRole
{
    Button,           // Interactive buttons
    CheckBox,         // Toggle controls
    ComboBox,         // Dropdown selectors
    Entry,            // Text input fields
    Label,            // Static text
    List,             // List containers
    ListItem,         // Individual list items
    Menu,             // Menu containers
    MenuItem,         // Menu options
    Panel,            // Generic containers
    ProgressBar,      // Progress indicators
    RadioButton,      // Mutually exclusive options
    ScrollBar,        // Scrolling controls
    Slider,           // Range selectors
    Table,            // Grid/table structures
    TableCell,        // Grid cells
    TextFrame,        // Multi-line text
    ToolBar,          // Toolbar containers
    // ... and 22+ more roles
}
```

## Implementing Accessibility in Custom Controls

When creating custom controls, you implement the `IAccessible` interface to expose semantic information:

```csharp
public class CustomToggle : SkiaView, IAccessible
{
    public AccessibleRole Role => AccessibleRole.CheckBox;

    public string Name => _label;

    public string Description => "Toggle for enabling feature";

    public AccessibleStates States
    {
        get
        {
            var states = AccessibleStates.Enabled | AccessibleStates.Focusable;
            if (IsChecked)
                states |= AccessibleStates.Checked;
            if (IsFocused)
                states |= AccessibleStates.Focused;
            return states;
        }
    }

    public void RaiseAccessibilityEvent(AccessibleEvent eventType)
    {
        // Notify assistive technologies of state changes
        AccessibilityManager.RaiseEvent(this, eventType);
    }
}
```

## Accessibility States and Properties

OpenMaui tracks **25+ accessibility states** that describe an element's current condition:

- **Enabled/Disabled**: Whether the control accepts input
- **Focused**: Current keyboard focus location
- **Checked/Unchecked**: Toggle state for checkboxes and radio buttons
- **Expanded/Collapsed**: State of collapsible elements
- **Selected**: Selection state in lists and grids
- **Pressed**: Active state during interaction
- **ReadOnly**: Whether content can be modified

When these states change, OpenMaui automatically fires AT-SPI2 events:

```csharp
protected override void OnPropertyChanged(string propertyName)
{
    base.OnPropertyChanged(propertyName);

    if (propertyName == nameof(IsEnabled))
    {
        RaiseAccessibilityEvent(AccessibleEvent.StateChanged);
    }
    else if (propertyName == nameof(Text))
    {
        RaiseAccessibilityEvent(AccessibleEvent.TextChanged);
    }
}
```

## Hierarchical Navigation

AT-SPI2 represents your UI as a tree structure. Screen readers navigate this tree using parent-child relationships:

```csharp
public interface IAccessible
{
    IAccessible Parent { get; }
    IReadOnlyList<IAccessible> Children { get; }
    int IndexInParent { get; }
}
```

OpenMaui's layout containers (`SkiaStackLayout`, `SkiaGrid`, `SkiaScrollView`) automatically maintain this hierarchy, ensuring screen readers can navigate through nested controls logically.

**Orca** is the most widely-used screen reader on Linux, bundled with GNOME and used across multiple desktop environments. OpenMaui applications work seamlessly with Orca through AT-SPI2 integration, providing a rich auditory interface for visually impaired users.

## Testing with Orca

To test your OpenMaui application with Orca:

```bash
# Install Orca (Ubuntu/Debian)
sudo apt install orca

# Launch Orca
orca &

# Run your OpenMaui app
dotnet run
```

Orca will announce each control as you navigate using keyboard shortcuts:

- **Tab/Shift+Tab**: Move between focusable elements
- **Arrow Keys**: Navigate within lists, menus, and grids
- **Space/Enter**: Activate buttons and toggle controls
- **Ctrl+Alt+Tab**: Switch between applications

## Providing Meaningful Labels

Screen readers rely on accurate, descriptive text. OpenMaui controls expose multiple text properties:

```csharp
// Good: Descriptive and contextual
new SkiaButton
{
    Text = "Save Document",
    AutomationId = "SaveButton",
    // Accessible name automatically derived from Text
};

// Better: Explicit accessible description for complex controls
new SkiaImageButton
{
    Source = "save-icon.svg",
    AccessibleName = "Save Document",
    AccessibleDescription = "Saves the current document to disk"
};

// Best: Contextual information for dynamic content
new SkiaLabel
{
    Text = $"Loading... {progress}%",
    AccessibleLiveRegion = LiveRegionMode.Polite,
    // Announces updates without interrupting user
};
```

## Live Regions for Dynamic Content

For content that updates frequently (progress indicators, notifications, chat messages), use **live regions** to announce changes:

```csharp
public enum LiveRegionMode
{
    Off,      // No announcements
    Polite,   // Announce when user is idle
    Assertive // Interrupt immediately
}

public class StatusPanel : SkiaStackLayout
{
    private SkiaLabel _statusLabel;

    public StatusPanel()
    {
        _statusLabel = new SkiaLabel
        {
            AccessibleLiveRegion = LiveRegionMode.Polite,
            AccessibleRole = AccessibleRole.StatusBar
        };
        Children.Add(_statusLabel);
    }

    public void UpdateStatus(string message)
    {
        _statusLabel.Text = message;
        // Orca will announce: "Status: File saved successfully"
    }
}
```

## Form Validation and Error Announcements

Accessible error handling ensures users understand validation failures:

```csharp
public class AccessibleEntry : SkiaEntry
{
    public static readonly BindableProperty ErrorMessageProperty =
        BindableProperty.Create(nameof(ErrorMessage), typeof(string), 
            typeof(AccessibleEntry), propertyChanged: OnErrorChanged);

    public string ErrorMessage
    {
        get => (string)GetValue(ErrorMessageProperty);
        set => SetValue(ErrorMessageProperty, value);
    }

    private static void OnErrorChanged(BindableObject bindable, 
        object oldValue, object newValue)
    {
        var entry = (AccessibleEntry)bindable;
        var error = (string)newValue;

        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(error))
        {
            entry.AccessibleDescription = $"Error: {error}";
            entry.States |= AccessibleStates.Invalid;
            entry.RaiseAccessibilityEvent(AccessibleEvent.StateChanged);
            // Orca announces: "Email address. Error: Invalid format"
        }
        else
        {
            entry.States &= ~AccessibleStates.Invalid;
        }
    }
}
```

## Testing Checklist for Screen Reader Support

Ensure your OpenMaui application meets these criteria:

✅ **All interactive elements are keyboard accessible**  
✅ **Every control has a meaningful accessible name**  
✅ **Form inputs have associated labels**  
✅ **Error messages are announced by screen readers**  
✅ **Dynamic content uses live regions appropriately**  
✅ **Focus order follows logical reading sequence**  
✅ **Modal dialogs trap focus and announce their purpose**  
✅ **Images have alternative text descriptions**  

OpenMaui's built-in accessibility support handles most of these automatically, but custom controls require explicit implementation.

High contrast mode is essential for users with visual impairments, providing enhanced readability through carefully selected color combinations. OpenMaui automatically detects high contrast themes across GNOME, KDE, and XFCE desktop environments and adapts your application's appearance accordingly.

## Detecting High Contrast Mode

OpenMaui's theme detection system monitors desktop environment settings through multiple channels:

```csharp
public class ThemeDetectionService
{
    public bool IsHighContrastMode { get; private set; }

    public void DetectTheme()
    {
        // GNOME: Check gsettings
        var gnomeTheme = GSettings.Get("org.gnome.desktop.interface", 
            "gtk-theme");
        if (gnomeTheme.Contains("HighContrast"))
        {
            IsHighContrastMode = true;
            return;
        }

        // KDE: Check kdeglobals
        var kdeConfig = KConfig.Read("kdeglobals", "General", 
            "ColorScheme");
        if (kdeConfig.Contains("HighContrast"))
        {
            IsHighContrastMode = true;
            return;
        }

        // XFCE: Check xfconf
        var xfceTheme = XfConf.Get("/Net/ThemeName");
        if (xfceTheme.Contains("HighContrast"))
        {
            IsHighContrastMode = true;
        }
    }
}
```

## WCAG Contrast Ratio Compliance

OpenMaui includes utilities to ensure your color choices meet **WCAG 2.1 Level AA** requirements (4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text):

```csharp
public static class ContrastCalculator
{
    public static double CalculateContrastRatio(Color foreground, 
        Color background)
    {
        var l1 = GetRelativeLuminance(foreground);
        var l2 = GetRelativeLuminance(background);

        var lighter = Math.Max(l1, l2);
        var darker = Math.Min(l1, l2);

        return (lighter + 0.05) / (darker + 0.05);
    }

    public static bool MeetsWCAGAA(Color foreground, Color background,
        bool isLargeText = false)
    {
        var ratio = CalculateContrastRatio(foreground, background);
        var threshold = isLargeText ? 3.0 : 4.5;
        return ratio >= threshold;
    }

    private static double GetRelativeLuminance(Color color)
    {
        var r = GetColorComponent(color.Red);
        var g = GetColorComponent(color.Green);
        var b = GetColorComponent(color.Blue);
        return 0.2126 * r + 0.7152 * g + 0.0722 * b;
    }

    private static double GetColorComponent(float value)
    {
        var v = value;
        return v <= 0.03928 ? v / 12.92 : Math.Pow((v + 0.055) / 1.055, 2.4);
    }
}
```

## Adaptive Color Palettes

Create theme-aware color schemes that automatically adapt to high contrast mode:

```csharp
public class AdaptivePalette
{
    private readonly ThemeDetectionService _themeService;

    public Color PrimaryText => _themeService.IsHighContrastMode
        ? Colors.White
        : Color.FromRgb(33, 33, 33);

    public Color SecondaryText => _themeService.IsHighContrastMode
        ? Color.FromRgb(200, 200, 200)
        : Color.FromRgb(117, 117, 117);

    public Color Background => _themeService.IsHighContrastMode
        ? Colors.Black
        : Colors.White;

    public Color AccentColor => _themeService.IsHighContrastMode
        ? Color.FromRgb(0, 255, 255)  // Cyan for maximum contrast
        : Color.FromRgb(98, 0, 238);   // Purple for standard mode

    public Color ButtonBackground => _themeService.IsHighContrastMode
        ? Color.FromRgb(0, 120, 215)   // High contrast blue
        : Color.FromRgb(0, 95, 184);   // Standard blue
}
```

## Implementing AppThemeBinding with High Contrast

Extend MAUI's `AppThemeBinding` to support high contrast mode:

```csharp
public class HighContrastThemeBinding : BindingBase
{
    public Color Light { get; set; }
    public Color Dark { get; set; }
    public Color HighContrast { get; set; }

    protected override object GetSourceValue(object value, Type targetType)
    {
        var themeService = Application.Current.Handler.MauiContext
            .Services.GetService<ThemeDetectionService>();

        if (themeService.IsHighContrastMode)
            return HighContrast;

        return Application.Current.UserAppTheme == AppTheme.Dark
            ? Dark
            : Light;
    }
}

// Usage in XAML
<Label TextColor="{local:HighContrastTheme 
    Light=#212121, 
    Dark=#FFFFFF, 
    HighContrast=#FFFFFF}" />
```

## Dynamic Theme Switching

Monitor system theme changes and update your application in real-time:

```csharp
public class ThemeMonitor
{
    private readonly LinuxApplication _app;
    private FileSystemWatcher _gnomeWatcher;

    public event EventHandler<ThemeChangedEventArgs> ThemeChanged;

    public void StartMonitoring()
    {
        // Monitor GNOME settings changes
        var settingsPath = Path.Combine(
            Environment.GetFolderPath(Environment.SpecialFolder.UserProfile),
            ".config/gtk-3.0/settings.ini"
        );

        _gnomeWatcher = new FileSystemWatcher(
            Path.GetDirectoryName(settingsPath),
            Path.GetFileName(settingsPath)
        );

        _gnomeWatcher.Changed += (s, e) =>
        {
            var isHighContrast = DetectHighContrastMode();
            ThemeChanged?.Invoke(this, new ThemeChangedEventArgs
            {
                IsHighContrast = isHighContrast
            });

            // Update all views
            _app.Dispatcher.Dispatch(() =>
            {
                UpdateApplicationTheme(isHighContrast);
            });
        };

        _gnomeWatcher.EnableRaisingEvents = true;
    }

    private void UpdateApplicationTheme(bool isHighContrast)
    {
        var palette = isHighContrast 
            ? HighContrastPalette.Instance 
            : StandardPalette.Instance;

        Application.Current.Resources["PrimaryColor"] = palette.Primary;
        Application.Current.Resources["BackgroundColor"] = palette.Background;
        Application.Current.Resources["TextColor"] = palette.Text;

        // Force re-render of all views
        foreach (var window in Application.Current.Windows)
        {
            (window.Handler.PlatformView as SkiaView)?.InvalidateVisual();
        }
    }
}
```

## Best Practices for High Contrast Support

1. **Never rely on color alone** to convey information—use icons, labels, or patterns
2. **Test with actual high contrast themes** (GNOME High Contrast, KDE High Contrast)
3. **Ensure focus indicators are visible** with at least 3:1 contrast against adjacent colors
4. **Provide sufficient padding** between interactive elements (minimum 44×44 pixels)
5. **Use semantic colors** from your theme palette rather than hardcoded values
6. **Avoid low-contrast overlays** like semi-transparent backgrounds over images

OpenMaui's rendering engine automatically adjusts shadows, borders, and focus indicators when high contrast mode is detected, ensuring your application remains usable without manual intervention.

Comprehensive keyboard navigation is the cornerstone of accessibility, enabling users to interact with your application without relying on a mouse. OpenMaui provides full keyboard support out of the box, with intelligent focus management and customizable navigation patterns.

## Tab Navigation and Focus Order

OpenMaui automatically establishes a logical tab order based on your visual hierarchy:

```csharp
public class LoginForm : SkiaContentPage
{
    public LoginForm()
    {
        Content = new SkiaStackLayout
        {
            Spacing = 16,
            Padding = 24,
            Children =
            {
                new SkiaLabel 
                { 
                    Text = "Username",
                    TabIndex = -1  // Not focusable
                },
                new SkiaEntry 
                { 
                    Placeholder = "Enter username",
                    TabIndex = 0,  // First in tab order
                    AutomationId = "UsernameEntry"
                },
                new SkiaLabel 
                { 
                    Text = "Password",
                    TabIndex = -1
                },
                new SkiaEntry 
                { 
                    Placeholder = "Enter password",
                    IsPassword = true,
                    TabIndex = 1  // Second in tab order
                },
                new SkiaButton 
                { 
                    Text = "Login",
                    TabIndex = 2,  // Third in tab order
                    Command = LoginCommand
                },
                new SkiaButton 
                { 
                    Text = "Cancel",
                    TabIndex = 3
                }
            }
        };

        // Set initial focus
        Loaded += (s, e) => 
        {
            var usernameEntry = this.FindByName<SkiaEntry>("UsernameEntry");
            usernameEntry?.Focus();
        };
    }
}
